        <h2>Forced labor in the armaments industry. The liberation of the Salzwedel satellite camp</h2>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8 mb-2 abstract">
                <p>
                    Even before the start of the Second World War, the National Socialists had begun to accelerate the expansion 
                    of the German arms industry. From 1933 to 1938 alone, armaments spending rose from four percent to over half 
                    of the national budget. German armaments companies profited from this armaments boom, but they were increasingly 
                    confronted with a shortage of labor.<sup><a href="#endnote1" id="footnote1">1</a></sup>
                    From 1942 onward, the National Socialists began to deploy concentration camp prisoners, too, in the German 
                    war industry. Starting in 1944, prisoners from the concentration and extermination camps in German-occupied 
                    Eastern Europe as well were deported to industrial sites in the German Reich for this purpose. The concentration 
                    camp prisoners were quartered in their own camps, the guarding of which continued to be organized by the SS, 
                    which was also paid for the prisoners’ work. Forced labor was a profitable way for the companies to increase 
                    their profits, which went hand in hand with the maximum exploitation of the labor of the malnourished and 
                    unprotected prisoners.<sup><a href="#endnote2" id="footnote2">2</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    When armaments production reached its peak in 1944, a total of 5.7 million foreign civilian workers, 1.9 million 
                    prisoners of war, and about 400,000 concentration camp inmates were working at production sites in the German Reich, 
                    accounting for almost a quarter of the workforce.<sup><a href="#endnote3" id="footnote3">3</a></sup> 
                    With the advance of the Allies, many armaments companies tried to get rid of the prisoners again, not least in 
                    order not to jeopardize their post-war position. The evacuation of the camps and the removal of the prisoners did 
                    not proceed uniformly and was characterized by the differing interests of the Nazi institutions and the confusing 
                    situation in the final months of the war.<sup><a href="#endnote4" id="footnote4">4</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
                <div class="infobox">
                    <h4>&#9432; Forced labor</h4>
                    <p>
                        National Socialist Germany made extensive use of forced labor to meet its labor needs; in the 
                        German Reich alone, over 13.5 million people had to perform forced labor during the Second World War. 
                        Forced labor was used in all branches of industry, but also in agriculture and in private households. 
                        Forced laborers were a visible part of everyday life in National Socialist Germany, especially in 
                        the final years of the war.
                    </p>
                    <p>
