        <h3 class="mt-4">Forced labor in Salzwedel</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    The Draht- und Metallwarenfabrik in Salzwedel, a wire and metal goods plant, profited from the German armaments 
                    boom as well; by 1937 it was the largest industrial company in Salzwedel with 600 employees. Foreign forced 
                    laborers were used at this location, too.<sup><a href="#endnote5" id="footnote5">5</a></sup>
                    In 1944, a camp that had previously been used for Eastern European forced laborers was converted into a satellite 
                    camp of the Neuengamme concentration camp.<sup><a href="#endnote6" id="footnote6">6</a></sup>
                    In the late summer of 1944, the first transport of female concentration camp prisoners who had been selected 
                    for work in Auschwitz arrived there. The group comprised mainly Jewish women who had only recently been deported 
                    from Hungary or the territories annexed by Hungary.<sup><a href="#endnote7" id="footnote7">7</a></sup> 
                    Some of the women had been deported to Auschwitz in May 1944 from the ghetto in what is today the Romanian 
                    city of Oradea. Many of the women came from Transcarpathia, today part of Ukraine, which had been awarded to 
                    Czechoslovakia in the interwar period and occupied by Hungary since 1939, for example from what is today the 
                    Ukrainian town of Tiachiv.
                </p>
                <h3 class="mt-4">Hungarian annexations and occupations during the Second World War</h3>
                <p>
                    From 1938 to 1941, Hungary, which was allied with Nazi Germany, annexed large areas of Czechoslovakia, Romania, 
                    and Yugoslavia. About 45 percent of the Jewish population of what was then Hungary lived in these areas when the 
                    country was occupied by Nazi Germany in 1944.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The former Czechoslovakian and Romanian regions of Hungary were among the first areas from which Jews were 
                    deported to the Auschwitz-Birkenau concentration and extermination camp. Not all of them spoke Hungarian or 
                    considered themselves to be Hungarian, but they all belonged to the group of Jews deported from Hungary.<sup><a href="#endnote8" id="footnote8">8</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
                <div class="infobox">
                    <h4>&#9432; Jewish men and women</h4>
                    <p>
                        The Jewish men and women deported from Hungary belonged to various communities and religious movements 
                        within Judaism. Not all of them necessarily defined themselves as Jewish. Neither their religion nor 
                        their cultural affiliation to Judaism or self-identification was decisive for their persecution by 
                        the National Socialists. At the heart of the National Socialist worldview was a racist antisemitism 
                        that defined Jews according to their descent. Christians and atheists were also persecuted as Jews by 
                        the National Socialists, regardless of their self-definition or cultural affiliation, if they met their 
                        criteria of descent. Not all of the persons referred to here as Jews identified themselves as Jewish, 
                        but they were all persecuted as Jewish.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="infobox mt-2">
                    <h4>&#9432; More on the historical background</h4>
                    <p>
                        <a href="{{ path('app_context') }}" title="Text on historical context">
                            &#10149; Historical context
                        </a>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-lg-8">
            <p>
                Survivors estimated the size of the first transport from Auschwitz to Salzwedel at around 500 women.<sup><a href="#endnote9" id="footnote9">9</a></sup>
                More female concentration camp prisoners were subsequently deported to the new satellite camp. Most of these 
                women had also been persecuted as Jews and came from Poland. However, some of the women also originated from 
                Italy, Czechoslovakia, Greece, the Netherlands, and Germany. The later transports also included larger groups of 
                women who had been deported from Hungary. The women in the subsequent transports, too, had been in the Auschwitz 
                concentration and extermination camp. Unlike the first transport, however, they were not deported directly to 
                Salzwedel but first to the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp, where they were selected for work in Salzwedel.<sup><a href="#endnote10" id="footnote10">10</a></sup>
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-lg-4">
            <div class="infobox mt-2">
                <h4>&#9432; The Bergen-Belsen concentration camp</h4>
                <p>
                    The Bergen-Belsen concentration camp was initially founded in 1943 as an “exchange camp” to quarter 
                    Jewish hostages. However, it was quickly assigned other functions and a men’s and women’s camp was set up. 
                    From the end of 1944 onward, Bergen-Belsen became the destination of many death marches and evacuation 
                    transports, developing into a death camp due to the appalling conditions. After liberation, a Polish 
                    and a Jewish displaced persons camp were set up in Bergen-Belsen.<sup><a href="#endnote11" id="footnote11">11</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <a href="{{ path('app_map') }}" title="Map overview">
                        &#10149; To the map of the camps
                    </a>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">The Salzwedel satellite camp</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    It is no longer possible to determine how many women were forced to work in the Salzwedel satellite camp, but 
                    surviving documents establish at least 1,518 women there.<sup><a href="#endnote12" id="footnote12">12</a></sup> 
                    Together with other forced laborers and German civilian workers, the women were supposed to ensure the production 
                    of infantry and anti-aircraft munitions in the Draht- und Metallwarenfabrik. Survivors, such as Kornélia Weisz, 
                    reported contact with and support from French prisoners of war in particular, as well as occasional help from 
                    German civilian workers.<sup><a href="#endnote13" id="footnote13">13</a></sup>
                    As in other satellite camps, the concentration camp prisoners had to work twelve-hour shifts, which, as survivors 
                    reported, were only interrupted by a 15-minute lunch break.<sup><a href="#endnote14" id="footnote14">14</a></sup> 
                    Survivors also recalled that they were given a slice of bread and a cup of coffee substitute in the morning, 
                    a soup consisting mainly of water at lunchtime, and another slice of bread in the evening. According to their 
                    reports, there was only one toilet barrack for the approximately 1,500 women.<sup><a href="#endnote15" id="footnote15">15</a></sup> 
                    The provisioning was thus similar to that of many satellite camps and led to the prisoners becoming exhausted 
                    and to the spread of diseases. A Hungarian Jewish woman was assigned to care for the sick, but she was only 
                    allowed to accept in eight to twelve women in the infirmary, where they were at least temporarily released 
                    from work. Some sick women were also taken to the city hospital, where they were not given any treatment but 
                    only the opportunity to recuperate. Seriously ill prisoners were deported to Bergen-Belsen as well. One can 
                    assume that many of these women were murdered there.<sup><a href="#endnote16" id="footnote16">16</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    According to survivors, there had been an increasing lack of material in the factory since the beginning of 1945 
                    and the civilian workers had stopped turning up. Survivor Mina Rapport reported furthermore that a German foreman 
                    warned her that the war would soon be over, as he feared that the prisoners would be murdered before liberation.<sup><a href="#endnote17" id="footnote17">17</a></sup> 
                    The work was probably stopped at the end of March 1945. Shortly afterward, the number of women almost doubled 
                    when transports from other satellite camps that had been evacuated arrived in Salzwedel. The new arrivals had 
                    previously survived various satellite camps in northwestern Germany and came mainly from the Porta 
                    Westfalica-Hausberge and Fallersleben satellite camps.
                </p>
