        <h3 class="mt-4">The prisoners from the Porta Westfalica-Hausberge satellite camp</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    The Porta Westfalica-Hausberge women’s satellite camp was established in February 1945. The approximately 
                    1,000 prisoners had to produce radio tubes for the Philipps company and its subsidiaries. The camp was 
                    evacuated in January 1945 and the prisoners were deported to various other satellite camps, including Fallersleben.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Some of the women, who had already been forced to produce radio tubes in a satellite camp of the Gross-Rosen 
                    concentration camp, were deported to Porta Westfalica in January 1945, first on foot and then on a freight 
                    train as the Soviet army approached. During this transport, the women were hardly provided with any food. 
                    Another group of women in Porta Westfalica came from the Horneburg satellite camp in the Hamburg area, where 
                    they had been forced to produce radio tubes as well. They had been selected for work in Auschwitz and were in 
                    Horneburg from October 1944 onward until being deported to Porta Westfalica-Hausberge in February 1945. All 
                    survivors describe the living and working conditions in the Porta Westfalica-Hausberge satellite camp as extremely 
                    cruel and brutal. As the Allies advanced in the west, too, the camp was evacuated on April 1, 1945 and the women 
                    were deported again. Some of the prisoners were sent to the Fallersleben satellite camp in present-day Wolfsburg.<sup><a href="#endnote18" id="footnote18">18</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
                <div class="infobox">
                    <h4>&#9432; Porta Westfalica concentration camp</h4>
                    <p>
                        The Porta Westfalica-Hausberge women’s satellite camp was established in February 1945. 
                        The approximately 1,000 prisoners had to produce radio tubes for the Philipps Company and its subsidiaries. 
                        The camp was evacuated in January 1945 and the prisoners were deported to various other satellite camps, 
                        including Fallersleben.
                    </p>
