        <h3 class="mt-4">The prisoners from the Fallersleben satellite camp</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    Like the Salzwedel satellite camp, the Fallersleben satellite camp for women was set up in the late summer of 1944. 
                    The first prisoners were also Jewish women who had been deported from Hungary to Auschwitz and had been selected by 
                    the SS for forced labor duty at the same time as the women in Salzwedel.<sup><a href="#endnote19" id="footnote19">19</a></sup>
                    In addition to the approximately 500 women from the first transport, other women from Bergen-Belsen arrived there 
                    as well, so that the camp’s workforce consisted of at least 650 women. The women were quartered in the VW factory 
                    near Fallersleben, today Wolfsburg, in pithead baths. The site had previously accommodated a group of 300 Jewish 
                    men who likewise had been deported from Hungary. The women had to work twelve-hour shifts at the VW factory 
                    producing plate mines and anti-tank rocket launchers. The provisions were the same as in other satellite camps. 
                    As the women were housed directly in the factory, they saw no daylight during their time there.
                </p>
                <img class="img-fluid" src="{{ asset('images/studies/salzwedel/CH11516_1 Tellerminen.jpg') }}"
                     alt="A forced laborer producing plate mines in Fallersleben"/>
                <p class="caption">
                    A forced laborer producing plate mines in Fallersleben; this work was later taken over by concentration camp prisoners. 
                    Courtesy of Volkswagen Aktiengesellschaft.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In the descriptions of Fallersleben by survivors such as Edréne Kovács, it must be taken into account that they 
                    assessed their imprisonment there against the background of their experiences in Auschwitz. This is the only 
                    way to understand why they emphasized the dry accommodation and the shower rooms, which would have offered the 
                    opportunity for at least a small degree of personal hygiene.<sup><a href="#endnote20" id="footnote20">20</a></sup> 
                    In March 1945, about 200 women arrived in Fallersleben from the Porta Westfalica-Hausberge satellite camp. 
                    Hanna Mandel, a survivor of the Fallersleben satellite camp, reported how depressed she had been by the 
                    condition of these women upon their arrival in Fallersleben and that panic had broken out among them when 
                    they were also led to the showers. The women who had survived Auschwitz feared that they would be murdered by 
                    poison gas shortly before the end of the war.<sup><a href="#endnote21" id="footnote21">21</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Die letzten Kriegswochen im Außenlager Salzwedel</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    Together, the women from the Fallersleben and Porta Westfalica-Hausberge satellite camps were deported again. 
                    The arrival of the women evacuated from the other satellite camps increased the number of prisoners in Salzwedel 
                    to around 3,000 women.<sup><a href="#endnote22" id="footnote22">22</a></sup>
                    The supply situation worsened once again as a result; survivors reported that the distribution of food had been 
                    stopped. The women were starving and sometimes fed on raw turnips.<sup><a href="#endnote23" id="footnote23">23</a></sup> 
                    Almost all survivors testified that in the final days before the liberation, there was concern that the prisoners 
                    would be deliberately murdered by blowing up the camp. Several survivors, such as Fela Gastwirth, reported that 
                    this was prevented by the French prisoners of war housed in the immediate vicinity of the satellite camp, who 
                    had learned of the plan and subsequently cut off the power supply.<sup><a href="#endnote24" id="footnote24">24</a></sup>
                    According to survivor Eva Braun, the French prisoners of war had also surrounded the camp and threatened the SS.<sup><a href="#endnote25" id="footnote25">25</a></sup> 
                    Survivor Hanna Mandel also recalled that she had been warned by French prisoners of war that the camp was to 
                    be set on fire. As a result, the women had loosened several boards in their barrack and set up a guard service 
                    at knotholes so that, if the barrack was set on fire, they could knock out the walls in time and attempt to 
                    escape. However, this did not happen.<sup><a href="#endnote26" id="footnote26">26</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    Some women also reported that the camp commandant had refused to murder the prisoners before the liberation. 
                    However, survivor Rose Brewster also pointed out that he had previously been promised by the responsible 
                    prisoner representatives that he would testify positively about him after the liberation.<sup><a href="#endnote27" id="footnote27">27</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The camp was liberated by American troops on April 14, 1945. Just a few kilometers away, the SS, Wehrmacht, 
                    and Volksturm units as well as Hitler Youth had burned to death 1,061 male concentration camp prisoners in a 
                    barn the day before in the Gardelegen massacre.
                </p>
                <img class="img-fluid" src="{{ asset('images/studies/salzwedel/T2694HäftlingszugHinten.jpg') }}"
                     alt="A group of male and female concentration camp prisoners seen from behind"/>
                <p class="caption">
                    Liberated male and female concentration camp prisoners in Gardelegen on June 5, 1945, 
                    private property, Johann-Friedrich-Danneil-Museum, Salzwedel.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
                <div class="infobox">
                    <h4>&#9432; Death marches and “final phase crimes”</h4>
                    <p>
                        In the final phase of the war, a number of concentration camps and satellite camps were evacuated by 
                        the Nazis before the approaching Allies arrived. The prisoners were either transported in freight cars, 
                        rarely in trucks, or forced to march on foot to areas still under German control. During the marches, 
                        which often lasted for days, sometimes even weeks, the prisoners were usually barely fed, many of them 
                        starving or dying of thirst in the freight cars, many collapsing during the marches due to exhaustion 
                        or being murdered by the SS or other units on guard duty. Survivors therefore coined the term “death march” 
                        for these evacuations. Some of the death marches ended in the targeted murder of prisoners, of which 
                        the so-called “Gardelegen massacre” constitutes one of the best known. More than 1,000 prisoners from 
                        satellite camps of the Neuengamme and Mittelbau-Dora concentration camps were rounded up in a field 
                        barn there, which was then set on fire by the SS and other Nazi organizations.<sup><a href="#endnote28" id="footnote28">28</a></sup>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">After the liberation</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    The survivor Gabriella Goitein reported:
                </p>
                <p class="quote">
                    „And then they said we could go. We walked this path, and it was a day of peace and there was sunshine. 
                    And the French, the prisoners of war, the French, they took us to their camp and we sat at long tables and 
                    they somehow [...] got bread and eggs. And they had these big pans and they broke the eggs onto the pan 
                    and mixed them. We sat there and I ate bread and eggs. That was my liberation.“<sup><a href="#endnote29" id="footnote29">29</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Many survivors, such as Kornélia Weisz, reported that the American soldiers, who were appalled by the women’s 
                    supplies and equipment, told them to look after themselves in the town.<sup><a href="#endnote30" id="footnote30">30</a></sup>
                    Many of the liberated concentration camp prisoners then left the camp and moved to the small town, where 
                    they looted food and clothes. The survivor Sándorné Margit Less told related, </p>
                <p class="quote">
                    „Then the gates were open and we ran out, one after the other. We didn’t know what to do. We had no normal clothes. 
                    We were dirty, teeming with lice. We hadn’t had anything to eat in the last few weeks, not even this thin 
                    turnip soup. Food, food was the only thing we thought about. After the liberation we went to a dairy. 
                    There were lots of different dairy products [...]. One woman found a soldier’s helmet and dipped it in milk, 
                    but these helmets had holes in them and the milk poured out of both sides. She drank, drank, and the milk flowed out. 
                    This image is the picture in my mind’s eye.“<sup><a href="#endnote31" id="footnote31">31</a></sup>
                </p>
                <img class="img-fluid"
                     src="{{ asset('images/studies/salzwedel/T2692Häftlingszugnah.jpg') }}"
                     alt="A Group of waving liberated women"/>
                <p class="caption">
                    Liberated women in the streets of Salzwedel, photo: Dale Ramsey, US Army, probably April 14, 1945, 
                    Johann-Friedrich-Danneil-Museum, Salzwedel.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In addition to looting stores and, for example, fabric in a department store, the liberated women also came into 
                    contact with the civilian population of Salzwedel. Even though some women recalled that they were initially driven 
                    by feelings of revenge and the survivor Klári Sztehlo reported that the inhabitants were afraid of the liberated 
                    concentration camp prisoners, there is no evidence of acts of violence.<sup><a href="#endnote32" id="footnote32">32</a></sup>
                    Years after the liberation, however, a town chronicle still contains formulations that emphasize above all the 
                    damage caused to the people of Salzwedel by the unregulated looting, without any sympathy for the prisoners and 
                    their situation.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The liberated prisoners were initially housed in former barracks at Salzwedel airfield, where the starving and 
                    often sick women were supposed to regain their strength. However, some of them died after liberation as a result 
                    of their imprisonment. Their graves can still be found in Salzwedel today. After some time, a number of the 
                    liberated women returned to their places of origin, whose national affiliation had changed again in the case 
                    of the women from Transcarpathia and the former Romanian territories. While the former became part of the 
                    Soviet Union, the other areas became part of Romania again. Quite a few of the surviving women decided against 
                    returning and initially remained as so-called “displaced persons” (DPs) under the care of the United Nations 
                    Relief and Rehabilitation Administration (UNRRA), an aid organization of the UN, until they emigrated to 
                    Western countries or to Palestine, the future state of Israel, which was under British Mandate rule at the time.
                </p>
