            </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Sources and research</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    Immediately after the liberation, a preserved list of the liberated women and their last places of residence 
                    was compiled. As a result, at least the names of the surviving women and their places of origin are known for 
                    the Salzwedel satellite camp.<sup><a href="#endnote33" id="footnote33">33</a></sup>
                    This constitutes a major difference to other satellite camps, whose surviving prisoners were generally 
                    liberated at other locations, which means that only very limited conclusions can be drawn about the places 
                    of imprisonment.
                </p>
        <!--
                <img class="img-fluid" style="width: 640px;" src="{{ asset('images/placeholder_840x560.jpg') }}"
                     alt="Interactive map of the places of origin "/>
                <p class="caption">
                    Map of the women's places of origin
                <p>
                -->
                    The majority of documents compiled by the Neuengamme satellite camp administration were destroyed before 
                    the liberation. Only a list from the SS site doctor in Neuengamme concerning occupancy of the satellite 
                    camps in March 1945 documents the number of inmates at that time. Even if this allows conclusions to be 
                    drawn about the size of the satellite camp, the sources of the National Socialist concentration camp 
                    administration are still bound to the perspective of the perpetrators, who robbed the prisoners of their 
                    humanity and individuality, reducing them to administrative challenges. This perpetrator source provides 
                    no insight into the biographical backgrounds of the prisoners or their individual living conditions. 
                    Nothing can be learned from these sources about the internees and their everyday experiences in the satellite 
                    camps. Other sources also provide only fragmentary information about the reality of the prisoners’ lives and 
                    their backgrounds. Until the 1990s, there was very little publicly available information about the Salzwedel 
                    satellite camp. In GDR times, a small model of the camp had already been exhibited in the Johann-Friedrich 
                    Danneil Museum and a brochure had been published, but this focused on the solidarity of some German workers 
                    with the persecuted. It was not until the 1990s that the first more comprehensive accounts appeared, based 
                    primarily on the documents of the British occupation authorities, who had begun investigations into the 
                    guards and had also interviewed survivors in the process. Although no guards were convicted, the documents 
                    have been preserved and are now an important source for historical research.<sup><a href="#endnote34" id="footnote34">34</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    As part of commemorative work, surviving women were also invited by the town of Salzwedel on several occasions 
                    from 1996 onward and interviewed about their time in detention.<sup><a href="#endnote35" id="footnote35">35</a></sup> 
                    The recollections shared by the women 50 years after liberation are molded by repression, forgetting, but also 
                    by the exchange with others. In addition, the interview situation itself as well shapes what is told and what 
                    is not told. Nevertheless, the memoirs are one of the most important sources for the history of the Salzwedel 
                    satellite camp. In addition, the Polish-born survivor Kitty Hart-Moxon began publishing about her time in the 
                    Auschwitz concentration and extermination camp and in various satellite camps – including Salzwedel – as early 
                    as the 1960s. Based on ten years of conversations between the theologian Norbert Rech and the Hungarian survivor 
                    Hanna Mandel, a book about her life was published as well in 2008.<sup><a href="#endnote36" id="footnote36">36</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    These survivors’ accounts form the basis for research, but also for the remembrance and commemoration 
                    of the Salzwedel satellite camp.
